Imagine a world where millions of children are forced to flee their homes, seeking safety in unfamiliar lands.Pakistan emerges as the largest host of refugee children under 18, followed closely by Turkey, Iran, and Uganda, placing a heavy burden on these nations.

Code 
import polars as pl
from plotnine import *
import geopandas as gpd
import plotly.express as px
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd


#Read file

df=pl.read_csv("/content/unicef_indicator_1.csv")


# Filter data for the year 2023

df_2023 = (df
  .filter(pl.col("year") == 2023)
)

#BAR GRAPH

df_pd = df_2023.to_pandas()

# Create a bar chart
bar_chart = (ggplot(df_pd, aes(x="country", y="obs_value"))  # Adjust column names accordingly
    + geom_bar(stat="identity", fill="blue")  # 'stat="identity"' is needed for numeric y-values
    + theme_minimal()
    + theme(
        axis_text_x=element_text(rotation=90, size=8),  # Rotate & adjust text size
        figure_size=(15, 6))
    + labs(
      x="COUNTRIES",
      y="Number of Refugees under 18",
      title="BAR GRAPH OF 2023")
)

bar_chart.show()

The bar chart highlights stark disparities, showing how some countries excel in child health and education while others struggle to meet basic needs.

Code 
#WORLD MAP
world = gpd.read_file("https://public.opendatasoft.com/api/explore/v2.1/catalog/datasets/world-administrative-boundaries/exports/shp")
(ggplot()
  + geom_map(world)
)

map_df_2023 = (world
  .merge(df.to_pandas(), left_on="name", right_on="country", how="outer")
)

map_2023 = (ggplot(data=map_df_2023)
  + aes(fill="obs_value")
  + geom_map()
  + coord_fixed()
  + theme(
        figure_size=(13, 6))
)

map_2023

The world map heatmap lays bare the global inequalities, with some regions glowing with progress while others remain in urgent need of intervention.

df_iran = (df

# Create a time series chart
time_series_plot = (ggplot(df, aes(x="year", y="obs_value", color="country"))  # Adjust column names
    + geom_line() # Line plot
    + guides(color="none")
    + theme_minimal()
    + theme(
        axis_text_x=element_text(rotation=90, size=10),  # Rotate x-axis labels
        figure_size=(15, 6)  # Increase figure size
    )
)

# Display the time series chart in Google Colab
time_series_plot.show()

The time-series chart tells a more dynamic story, tracking how child welfare indicators shift over time. Policy changes, global crises, and economic growth leave their imprints, shaping the futures of millions.

Code 
# Create a scatter plot with a regression line
scatter_plot = (ggplot(df_2023, aes(x=df_2023.columns[0], y=df_2023.columns[2]))  # Adjust column names
    + geom_point(color="blue")  # Scatter plot points
    + theme_minimal()
    + theme(
        axis_text_x=element_text(rotation=90, size=8),  # Rotate x-axis labels for readability
        figure_size=(15, 6)  # Increase figure size
    )
)

# Display the scatter plot in Google Colab
scatter_plot.show()
